{"type":"data","nodes":[{"type":"data","data":[{"debug":1},true],"uses":{}},{"type":"data","data":[{"zotero":1,"inscriptions":7,"isBulletin":131},{"title":2,"author":3,"date":4,"citation":5,"uri":6},"Due nuovi saturnii?","Wick","1926","\u003Cspan>F. C. Wick, «Due nuovi saturnii?», \u003Ci>Athenaeum\u003C/i> 4 (1926): 167–71\u003C/span>","https://www.zotero.org/groups/isicily/items/SP2B89MW",[8],{"file":9,"uri":9,"title":10,"status":11,"editionAuthor":13,"type":14,"objectType":18,"material":22,"condition":29,"layoutDesc":30,"handNote":37,"date":51,"places":55,"geo":65,"country":60,"provenance":57,"provenanceGeo":69,"region":72,"settlement":62,"repository":73,"textLang":74,"tmNumber":82,"facsimile":83,"letterHeights":90,"publications":93,"zotero":103,"keywords":113,"html":122,"bibl":123,"bulletinDateSort":128,"citedRangeSort":129,"languageSort":130,"materialSort":23,"typeSort":15},"ISic002753","Fragment of a bilingual dedication to Priapus",{"_":12},"draft",null,{"_":15,"ana":16,"ref":17},"dedication","#function.dedication","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/typeins/lod/88.html",{"_":19,"ana":20,"ref":21},"plaque","#object.plaque","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/259.html",{"_":23,"ana":24,"type":25,"subtype":26,"ref":28},"marble","#material.inorganic.stone.metamorphic_rock.marble","stone.marble",[27],"unverified","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/48.html","",{"layout":31},{"_":32,"rs":33,"damage":29},"Five lines of regularly spaced Greek letters followed by three lines of Latin letters. The first two lines of Latin text follow the same spacing as the Greek text; the final line is seemingly centered, more widely spaced (with interpuncts) and separated by a slightly greater interval from the lines above. Although the top of the stone is damaged, the visible space above line 1 is greater than that between the following lines.\n                                    \n                                \t\n\t\t\t",{"_":34,"ana":35,"ref":36},"chiselled","#execution.chiselled","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1",{"lettering":38,"dimensions":39},"Regular, well-cut Greek letters with clearly defined serifs at the end of strokes: Omicron, omega and theta all have rhomboid form; in some instances this is actually a pentagonal form, flat across the top; Omega is open at the bottom; Sigma is four bar and regular; Epsilon has equal horizontal strokes; Alpha has broken bar; the diagonal of the Nu starts and finishes well below/above the ends of the vertical strokes. The Latin letters show the beginnings of the move towards cursive forms: M has extended upper strokes and the midpoint reaches to the bottom of the line; A also has extended upper stroke and lacks a cross-bar; O is rounded, in contrast to the Greek text, as is Q with extended tail; P is open; R is closed; E has short upward slanting strokes; L has a long foot, forming almost a C.",[40,47],{"type":41,"l":42,"from":43,"to":44,"h":45,"unit":46,"atLeast":45,"atMost":45},"letterHeight","Lines 1-8","line1","line8","20","mm",{"type":48,"l":49,"from":43,"to":50,"unit":46},"interlinear","Interlineation\n                                ","line2",{"_":52,"notBefore":53,"notAfter":54},"Late 2nd — 4th century CE",180,400,[56,61],{"_":57,"type":58,"ref":59,"region":60},"Acium","ancient","http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462067","Sicilia",{"_":62,"type":63,"ref":64,"region":60},"Aci San Antonio","modern","http://sws.geonames.org/2525383",[66],[67,68],37.57533,15.17411,[70,71],37.598818,15.126647,"Sicily","unknown",{"_":75,"mainLang":76,"otherLangs":77,"ana":78,"languages":79},"Ancient Greek and Latin","grc","la","#bilingualism.biversion.complementary",[80,81],"Ancient Greek","Latin","175851",{"n":84,"url":85,"height":86,"width":87,"desc":88,"surfaceType":89},"screen","ISic002753_tiled.tif","2790px","3431px","Scan of photo in NSA 1922 p.494 fig.2","front",[91],{"atLeast":92,"atMost":92},20,[94,95,95,95,95,96,97,98,99,96,100,101,102],"L'année épigraphique: revue des publ